# AI Coding Agent Instructions

This project is designed for AI-assisted frontend development. Follow these rules unless a human maintainer explicitly changes the project process.

## Language Rules

- All code comments, UI labels, component names and developer-facing names must be in English.
- Product planning documents may be written in Czech or English.
- Keep naming consistent across PRDs, flows, screens, components, composables and tests.

## Required Reading Before Implementation

Before implementation, read the relevant:

- PRD in `product/prds/`
- user flow in `product/user-flows/`
- screen spec in `product/screens/`
- feature spec in `product/features/`
- task in `project/backlog/`
- related architecture or API contract in `docs/`

If any required document is missing or contradicts another document, update the task with the gap before editing code.

## Workflow

Use this sequence:

Vision -> Personas -> User flows -> Screens -> UI states -> Component model -> API contracts -> Tasks -> Implementation -> Tests -> ADRs

Start from product intent. Define the user flow, screen states, data requirements, component tree and API contracts before building UI. Implement vertical slices that include the UI, state, API integration and tests needed for one user-visible outcome.

## Frontend Rules

- Prefer small vertical slices.
- Do not start from components; start from user flow and screen state.
- Keep components small.
- All UI must use design tokens from `design/design-tokens.md` and `app/assets/css/tokens.css`.
- Do not invent new colors, spacing, radius or shadows inside components.
- If a new visual pattern is needed, update `design/design-tokens.md` first.
- Do not implement pixel-perfect design before flows are functional.
- Use composables for reusable logic.
- Use stores only for shared application state.
- Avoid global state for local UI state.
- Do not put server-only logic into client code.
- Every non-trivial UI must handle loading, empty and error states.
- Use `<script setup lang="ts">` in Vue components.
- Keep accessibility requirements visible while designing screen states.

## State And Data

- Local UI state belongs in the component that owns the interaction.
- Reusable logic belongs in `app/composables/`.
- Shared application state belongs in `app/stores/` only when multiple distant screens or components need it.
- Server-only secrets, privileged API calls and persistence logic belong in `server/`.

## Tasks And Tests

- Every task should update `project/TASK_SEQUENCE.md` if the backlog changes.
- Every implementation task should include tests when practical.
- User-visible changes should update `CHANGELOG.md`.
- Unit-test composables and pure logic.
- Use E2E tests for critical flows and high-value regressions.
- Keep tests focused on behavior rather than implementation details.

## Definition Of Done

A task is done only when:

- The implemented behavior matches the linked PRD, user flow, screen spec and API contract.
- Loading, empty, ready and error states are handled for every non-trivial UI path.
- UI styling uses documented design tokens only.
- Keyboard access, focus states, labels and error messaging are checked for changed screens.
- Relevant unit, typecheck, lint and E2E coverage is added or an explicit test gap is recorded.
- `{{ package_manager }} run check` passes locally before handoff.
- `CHANGELOG.md`, task notes and ADRs are updated when the change affects users, architecture or dependencies.

## Dependencies And Decisions

- Do not add large dependencies without an ADR.
- Record significant architecture, state-management, API and design-system decisions in `docs/decisions/`.
- Prefer Nuxt conventions and existing project patterns before adding custom abstractions.
